  "dateModified": "2026-04-30",
  "datePublished": "2026-04-30",
  "description": "Scansion is the analytic technique for marking, on the page, which syllables of a line of metrical verse are stressed and which are unstressed, so that the meter the line is keeping — and the places it departs from that meter — can be read off explicitly. The word comes from Latin scandere (\u0026ldquo;to climb\u0026rdquo;), via the medieval grammarians\u0026rsquo; practice of climbing a line foot by foot to verify its measure.\nTo scan a line is to make its metrical contract visible. The reader who can scan can say with precision: this is iambic pentameter, with a trochaic substitution in the first foot and a feminine ending after the fifth. The reader who cannot scan can hear that the line is metrical and feel the substitutions, but cannot name what is happening or why a different line at a different point in the poem is doing something subtly different.\n",
  "name": "Scansion",
